\layout Subsection

Polynomial Representation
\layout Standard

One can attempt to solve GKW by working in the polynomial representation.
 One possible choice is to make one's Taylor expansion about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset 

, but this turns out to be a very poor choice, as we shall soon see.
 Thus, if we write 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{h}f=g$
\end_inset 

 and substitute a Taylor's expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset 

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{g^{(m)}(0)}{m!}=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\frac{f^{(k)}(0)}{k!}\,(-)^{m}\;\frac{(k+m+1)!}{m!\,(k+1)!}\,\zeta(k+m+2)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 or, adopting the bra-ket notation introduced earlier, we have 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left\langle m\left|U_{h}\right|k\right\rangle =(-)^{m}\;\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m\end{array}\right)\,\zeta(k+m+2)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where we've replaced the factorials by the binomial coefficient that they
 form.
 Unfortunately, this is clearly a very poorly conditioned matrix.
 One can make some progress, if one wishes, by applying a regulator and
 using Levin-type sequence acceleration techniques.
 One can thus find a number of curious identities, some of which we've listed
 previously.
 However, the difficulty of working with divergent sums seems to outweigh
 any advantages given by the relatively simple form of the matrix elements.
 Thus, we are lead to consider the matrix elements for a polynomial expansion
 about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset 

.
 These are far more complex, but give a very well-conditioned matrix.
 These are: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
G_{mn}=\sum_{k=0}^{n}(-)^{k}\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
k\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
k+m+1\\
m\end{array}\right)\,\left[\zeta(k+m+2)-1\right]\label{eq:GKW-matrix-elts}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
(-)^{m}\frac{g^{(m)}(1)}{m!}=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}G_{mn}(-)^{n}\frac{f^{(n)}(1)}{n!}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Other authors have chosen to expand about 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1/2$
\end_inset 

 [need ref here] but as can be seen the above is a more tractable expression.
 (copy the x=1/2 expansion here).
 
\layout Standard

The first eigenvalue is known as the GKW constant, and is about 0.3036.
\layout Standard

The eigenvector equation to be solved is then 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}G_{mn}v_{n}=\lambda v_{m}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $v=\{ v_{n}\}$
\end_inset 

 is an eigenvector with components 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n}$
\end_inset 

.
 This beast has a discrete spectrum (need reference for proof), and so we
 may label the eigenvalues and eigenvectors with a label 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

, so that the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

'th eigen equation is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}G_{mn}v_{nk}=\lambda_{k}v_{mk}\label{eq:Eigenvalue eqn}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

'th polynomial eigenfunction of the GKW operator is then given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho_{k}(x)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}v_{nk}(1-x)^{k}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The zeroth eigenfunction was given by Gauss as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\rho_{0}(x)=\frac{1}{1+x}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and corresponds to the eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n0}=2^{-n}$
\end_inset 

.
 Again, we note the curious appearance of powers of two.
\layout Standard

Based on numerical explorations (reported below), the series appears to
 be easily convergent even for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset 

.
 In particular, it appears that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}v_{nk}=0$
\end_inset 

, and that furthermore, that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}v_{nk}/v_{n+1,k}=2$
\end_inset 

.
 One must not conclude that this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{nk}~\mathcal{O}(2^{-n})$
\end_inset 

, as this sort of asymptotic behaviour conflicts with the zeroth eigenfunction.
 Thus, one might guess at 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{nk}~\mathcal{O}(n^{s}2^{-n})$
\end_inset 

 but numeric data suggests that 
\begin_inset Formula $s=0$
\end_inset 

.
 Numeric data also excludes the form 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{nk}~\mathcal{O}(2^{-n}\log n)$
\end_inset 

 although it is possible that the softer 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{nk}~\mathcal{O}(2^{-n}\log\log n)$
\end_inset 

 might hold.
\layout Standard

The coefficients are oscillatory, with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

 half-oscillations in the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset 

'th eigenvector.
 That is, for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset 

, all of the 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n0}$
\end_inset 

 can be taken to be of the same sign.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1$
\end_inset 

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{n1}$
\end_inset 

 change sign, once, between 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset 

.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $k=2$
\end_inset 

, the coefficients change sign twice, and so on.
 This is shown in the graph below.
 
\layout Standard

The left eigenvectors are given by 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}w_{km}G_{mn}=\lambda_{k}w_{kn}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and correspond to left eigenfunctions 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\ell_{k}(x)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}w_{kn}(-1)^{n}\delta^{(n)}(1-x)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{(n)}(x)$
\end_inset 

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

'th derivative of the Dirac delta function.
 The zeroth left eigenvector is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{0n}=1/(n+1)$
\end_inset 

.
 Very curiously, this is the harmonic series.
 Thus, true to form, it appears that yet again, we are in the presence of
 another manifestation of the duality between the dyadic rationals and rationals
, the duality between the Stern-Brocot tree and the dyadic tree, the duality
 captured in the Minkowski Question Mark function.
\layout Standard

In analogy to the right eigenvectors, the series again appears to be not
 only convergent in that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}w_{kn}=0$
\end_inset 

, but also that a strict ratio is maintained in the limit: 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{n\to\infty}(n+2)\, w_{kn}/(n+1)\, w_{k,n+1}=1$
\end_inset 

, with strict equality holding for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

, and not just in the limit, when 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset 

.
 A similar oscillatory behaviour is shown as well.
\layout Subsection

Identity
\layout Standard

We have the identity
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}G_{mn}p^{-n}=p\left[\zeta(m+1)-1-\zeta\left(m+1,2+\frac{1}{p-1}\right)\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 In particular, for 
\begin_inset Formula $p=2$
\end_inset 

, the right hand side equals 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{-m}$
\end_inset 

; this corresponds to the known eigenvector.
 Note that for any value of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

, the leading term on the right is 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{-(m+1)}$
\end_inset 

.
 A simple way to arrive at this is to note that 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}p^{-n}(1-x)^{n}=\frac{p}{p-1+x}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and then evaluate this simple expression under the action of the GKW operator.
\layout Subsection

The Kernel
\layout Standard

We would like to know what the kernel of the GKW operator is.
 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
k(x)=\frac{1}{x^{2}}\exp(2k+1)\frac{\pi}{x}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\left[U_{h}k\right](x) & = & \exp\left((2k+1)\pi x\right)\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\cos(2k+1)n\pi\nonumber \\
 & = & \exp\left((2k+1)\pi x\right)\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}(-)^{n}\label{eq:}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset 

 The value of the sum is ambiguous.
 One is tempted to cancel terms pairwise, and thus declare 
\begin_inset Formula $k(x)$
\end_inset 

 to belong to the kernel.
 On the other hand, we've seen that the regularized sum is not zero: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\,(-)^{k}e^{-tk}=\frac{1}{2}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 and so one is left in a bit of a quandary.
 
\layout Standard

Some progress might be made by applying the theory of the Henstock-Kurzweil
 integral.
